description: From Middle English *fak, fec, fæc (“space, compartment”), from Old English fæc (“space of time, while, division, interval; period of five years, lustrum”), from Proto-West Germanic *fak, from Proto-Germanic *faką (“division, department, space”), from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ǵ-, *paǵ- (“to fasten, fix”). Cognate with West Frisian fek, Dutch vak (“section, compartment”), German Fach (“compartment”), Swedish fack (“compartment, box, department”), Latin pangō (“fasten, fix”).

entries.meaning: (UK dialectal) One of the four stomachs of a ruminating animal; rumen; paunch.

verbs.description: fack (third-person singular simple present facks, present participle facking, simple past and past participle facked)

entries.meaning: (UK, Cockney, vulgar) Pronunciation spelling of fuck.
